                                Report abuseTranscript of SM 439 Presentationphoto credit Nasa / Goddard Space Flight Center / Reto Stöckli Suzanne Lavelle Baumgartner Jump: What Red Bull Gets Out Of It Summary of the article On Sunday October 14, 2012, Skydiving pro Felix Baumgartner successfully jumped 24 miles to Earth, breaking a world record set more than 50 years ago. Red Bull took full financial responsibility in regards to developing, implementing, and staffing the jump. Relevance Question #1 On what ground could Red Bull base their market segmentation off of? Question #2 How is this sponsorship different from others? Question #3 Does this sponsorship establish any congruency/fit between the sponor and sponsee? Source Rooney, J. (2012, October 15). Baumgartner jump: What red bull gets out of it. Retrieved from http://www.forbes.com/sites/jenniferrooney/2012/10/15/baumgartner-jump-what-red-bull-gets-out-of-it/print/ Red Bull supports about 600 athletes worldwide: (120 in the U.S.) in 160 different kind of sports and invests about one third of its turnover in marketing. Felix is one of the first Red Bull athletes. Red Bull Stratos is an example of how Red Bull helps its athletes to achieve their professional goals, and the program is one that Red Bull developed together with Felix Baumgartner over the last five years. Red Bull is proud to "sponsor" these types of events because the energy drink company then receives credit for creating the equipment necessary to help these atheltes reach their personal goals , while also delivering valuable physiological and other fields of data to the scientific community. In my opinion, yes. Red Bull has established a strong brand association as being a sponsor of extreme athletes and events, and has a heritage in flying, through its partnerships with aeronautic teams as well as its popular Flying Day events, featuring human-powered vehicles Red Bull was able to demonstrate how to achieve  competitive edge in the beverage industry through the use of sponsorship.Red Bull has positioned themselves  as a product for adventure sports, extreme sports, and outdoor sports. This particular sponsorship reinforced their positioning on a global level.Due to the use of the space jump, Red Bull has been able to establish, and hopefully in the long-term maintain, product differentiation and brand equity. Red Bull  also created a unique positioning opportunity that will in return further create and maintain customer intimacy and loyalty. I also believe that because of these unique sponsorships, Red Bull has created an advantage concerning the area of category exclusivity. Psychographic Personality & Values Benefits sought Product knowledge "Gives You Wings" Energy drink Extremist Trendsetters Athleticism Increase energy Increase performance (cc) image by anemoneprojectors on Flickr In the eyes of Felix Baumgartner, I think he saw Red Bull as more as a partner then "sponsor" status. The organization and Felix worked together for seven years in order to make this jump successful, whereas most sponsorships are not as enduring. Also Red Bull was the backbone behind this event. They are credited with the creation of this event. It wasn't Baumgartner who found Red Bull, it was Red Bull who found Baumgartner. If you go through the chronicles throughout the past years, you will easily be able to identify Red Bull as the being more than just involved in the implemtation and execution of this jump. Finally, if you have watched the jump, the Red Bull logo is identified almost everywhere possible where most sponsorships aren't publisized to such an extent.Full transcriptMore presentations by
    
        
            Suzanne Lavelle
